V. Analysis ot De Materia.

Though the text of this tractate is less corrupt than that of the former three, if we consider each sentence in particular, it is not less difficult to analyze than they are. There is a great gap, —- Ι think between pages 172 and 1733 indeed it would seem as though what precedes p. 173 has no connection whatever with the rest of the treatise. The title, De Materia, is merely conjectural (see Shirley's Cata- logue) and nothing more is said about matter after p. 172. This indeed is not a sufficient reason to conclude that these two parts are fragments of different treatises, for Wyclis is often given to wandering far from his subject3 but it authorizes us in analyzing the two parts separately.

First Part (p. 170—173). Primal matter never can be a predicate. This means, not that we cannot say of any given body, This is matter; but that it is the first underlying subject of all forms3 all forms or determinations are therefore predicable of it, and not vice versa. We say truly‚ This is matter, but then we mean determined matter, not the first underlying subject. The question is, whether this primordia] matter is absolutely formless in its essence.
